Rena Repenning and Eddy Salazer¶

CURRENT VERSION: UPDATED AS Of night 11/16

Project Plan¶

Data¶

  1. We Play Data 1 Provided by Christine Neely

Explanation¶

We are inspired by The We Play center's mission: "to offer a safe place to play while engaging in activities that promote brain development." Melanie Richardson expressed a need for statistical evidence of We Play's importance.

Methodology¶

First, we manually removed empty columns and rows from the five excel files. Then, we broke apart sheets to make data frames adressing a single concern. Using these dataframes we began crafted questions to answer with available data. In December we plan to meet with Melanie to get feedback on our efforts.

We plan on answering:

  • How families found WePLAY
  • Why parents haven't applied for childcare
  • How parents interact with their kids
  • What kind of information do parents want more of
  • What will keep parents coming back

Collaboration Plan¶

Rena and Eddy will utilize this repository to simultaneously edit the project. We plan on connecting over Zoom as needed and keeping constant communication over instant message. Also, we are both able to meet after class on Thursdays. When convinient, we will export notebooks to Google Colabs to support simultaneous editing. (This is easily done using a Colabs Chrome extension).

Footnotes¶

1. WePLAY data was last downloaded on October 25th, 2021. We could not use a live link because of spaces in filenames.

Exploring WePLAY Survey Results¶

Provided by Christine Neely from WePlay by Training Grounds nola. Data last accessed on October 25th.

##
## possible function to use when plotting graphs to save code

def plotPies(df, labels, numCols, cols):
    fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=numCols,figsize=(13,3))
    for i, c in enumerate(cols):
        ax = ax1[i].pie(df[c].value_counts(), autopct='%1.1f%%',
                shadow=True, startangle=90, labels=labels)
        ax1[i].set_title(cols[i])
        ax1[i].axis('equal')
        #ax[0] is the "wedges" part of the pie that the plotting returns
        ax1[i].legend(ax[0], labels[i],
              title="Legend",
              loc="center left",
              bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0, 0.5, 1))
    plt.show()

child_FD.drop(columns=["age2", "age3", "age4", "misc", "parent"], inplace=True)
labels = [ ["Male", "Female"], 
          ["0-6 months", "7-12 months", "13-18 months", "19-24 months", "25-36 months", "37 months or more"]]
child_FD["Gender"][~(child_FD.Gender == 'Male' ) & ~(child_FD.Gender == 'Female')] = np.nan

titles = ["Child's Gender", "Child's Age Range"]
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=2,figsize=(13,3))
for i, c in enumerate(child_FD.columns):
    ax1[i].pie(child_FD[c].value_counts(), autopct='%1.1f%%',
            shadow=True, startangle=90, labels=labels[i])
    ax1[i].set_title(titles[i])
    ax1[i].axis('equal')
plt.show()
